The party says there were heavily armed members of the military police and other members of the SANDF inside the parliamentary precinct. CAPE TOWN - The Democratic Alliance (DA) will approach the Western Cape High Court over the deployment of army officials in the parliamentary precinct during the State of the Nation Address (Sona) on Thursday night.The opposition party made the announcement during a media briefing on Friday.The party says there were heavily armed members of the military police and other members of the national force inside the parliamentary precinct.The DA says it has instructed its lawyers to file an application in the Western Cape High Court, seeking a declaration that the deployment of army members on the precinct for non-ceremonial purposes, was unconstitutional and unlawful.The party says that the presence of the South African National Defence Force (SANDF), in a way that far exceeded a mere ceremonial role, can t be tolerated.The party adds that the excessive use of force by parliamentary security officials, the use of pepper spray in the public gallery and the Speaker's flouting of proper procedure for the expulsion of members from the Chamber, should all be declared unlawful and unconstitutional.(Edited by Winnie Theletsane)